        "title": "Java: Converting UTF 8 to String",
        "body": "<p>When I run the following program:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public static void main(String args[]) throws Exception\n{\n    byte str[] = {(byte)0xEC, (byte)0x96, (byte)0xB4};\n    String s = new String(str, \"UTF-8\");\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>on Linux and inspect the value of s in jdb, I correctly get: <\/p>\n\n<pre><code> s = \"ì\u2013´\"\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>on Windows, I incorrectly get:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>s = \"?\"\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>My byte sequence is a valid UTF-8 character in Korean, why would it be producing two very different results?<\/p>\n",
