            "last_activity_date": 1349212936,
            "creation_date": 1349212936,
            "body": "<p>It correctly prints \"<code>어<\/code>\" on my computer (Ubuntu Linux), as described in <a href=\"http://lcweb2.loc.gov/diglib/codetables/9.3.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><em>Code Table Korean Hangul<\/em><\/a>. Windows command prompt is known to have issues with encoding, don't bother.<\/p>\n\n<p>Your code is fine.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 12698537,
            "question_id": 12698447
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/07ej2.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 70258,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 203907,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/203907/bozho",
                "reputation": 599094,
                "display_name": "Bozho",
                "accept_rate": 81
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1349212811,
            "creation_date": 1349212811,
            "body": "<p>It gives <code>어<\/code> for me. This means your console is probably not configured to display UTF-8 and it is a printing/display problem, rather than a problem with representation.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 12698498,
            "question_id": 12698447
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4af3541c00d591e9a518b9c0b3b1190a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 134022,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 335858,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/335858/sergey-kalinichenko",
                "reputation": 729237,
                "display_name": "Sergey Kalinichenko",
                "accept_rate": 81
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1349212880,
            "creation_date": 1349212880,
            "body": "<p>You get the correct string, it's Windows console that does not display the string correctly.<\/p>\n\n<p>Here is a <a href=\"http://blog.maurus.be/index.php/2011/03/unicode-windows-console-output-and-java/\" rel=\"nofollow\">link<\/a> to an article that discusses a way to make Java console produce correct Unicode output using JNI.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 12698517,
            "question_id": 12698447
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4dffc7284fb151ce2c8e128ad711951d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1873836,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1695500,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1695500/dan-bliss",
                "reputation": 1764,
                "display_name": "Dan Bliss"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1349213751,
            "creation_date": 1349213751,
            "body": "<p>JDB is displaying the data incorrectly.  The code works the same on both Windows and Linux.  Try running this more definitive test:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n    byte str[] = {(byte)0xEC, (byte)0x96, (byte)0xB4};\n    String s = new String(str, \"UTF-8\"); \n    for(int i=0; i&lt;s.length(); i++) {\n        System.out.println(BigInteger.valueOf((int)s.charAt(i)).toString(16));\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This prints out the hex value of every character in the string.  This will correctly print out \"c5b4\" in both Windows and Linux.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 12698711,
            "question_id": 12698447
        }
    ],
